@Node "Overview" "snapconv.info/Overview"
@Next "Invoking SnapConv"
@Prev "Copying"
@Toc "Main"

Overview
********

   SnapConv is a program designed for use with Spectrum emulators
(programs which make your computer `pretend' to be a Sinclair Spectrum,
a home computer released in 1982; a variant was sold in the US as the
Timex TS2068). If you have no idea what I'm talking about, visit the ZX
Spectrum FAQ, available on the World Wide Web, at
`http://www.kendalls.demon.co.uk/cssfaq/index.html'.

   The vast selection of Spectrum emulators which are now available use
a large selection of snapshot formats, and often don't provide any
method for converting between a format which they do support and any
formats which they don't. Whilst there are some snapshot convertors
already available (notably SpConv by Henk de Groot and Damien Burke),
each has its own disadvantages (for example, SpConv can't handle 128Kb
snaps).


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking SnapConv" "snapconv.info/Invoking SnapConv"
@Next "File Formats"
@Prev "Overview"
@Toc "Main"

Running SnapConv
****************

   To convert SNAP1 to SNAP2, simply enter

   `snapconv [OPTIONS] SNAP1 SNAP2'

   The type of snapshot being converted from and to will be recognised
by the extensions of SNAP1 and SNAP2; the extension for each file
format is listed in its entry under `File Formats' (see @{"File Formats" Link "File Formats"}).
Currently, the supported extensions are `.sna', `.snp', `.sp', `.z80'
and `.zxs'.

   SnapConv can also extract the screen from a snapshot file; See @{"scr" Link "scr"}.


 @{" File type options " Link "File type options"}            Forcing different formats and versions
 @{" Changing hardware " Link "Changing hardware"}            Changing the machine and peripherals
 @{" Verbose " Link "Verbose"}                      Getting more messages
 @{" R register " Link "R register"}                   Problems with the R register


@EndNode

@Node "File type options" "snapconv.info/File type options"
@Next "Changing hardware"
@Prev "Invoking SnapConv"
@Toc "Invoking SnapConv"

Selecting the file type
=======================

   If you wish to use a different extension for a specific snapshot
format, or you wish to use a snapshot format which does not have a
commonly used extension, for example the +D snapshot format (see
@{"PlusD" Link "PlusD"}), you must tell SnapConv which format you are using. This is done
with the `-i SNAPTYPE' and `-o SNAPTYPE' options to select the input
and output formats respectively. The supported values of SNAPTYPE are
listed in each entry under `File Formats' (see @{"File Formats" Link "File Formats"}).

   Secondly, certain formats have multiple versions; SnapConv has a
default version for each format, but you may wish to create a different
format. This can be accomplished with the `-1', `-2' and `-3' options;
again, the specific action for each format can be found in its entry
under See @{"File Formats" Link "File Formats"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Changing hardware" "snapconv.info/Changing hardware"
@Next "Verbose"
@Prev "File type options"
@Toc "Invoking SnapConv"

Changing the machine type and peripherals
=========================================

   You may wish to change the machine type which is in a snapshot, or to
change the additional peripherals which are attached to that machine.
This can be accomplished via the `-m', `-p' and `-q' options.

   The `-m' option takes one argument, which is the machine type to
change to. Possible arguments are:

   * `48': selects a standard 48K Spectrum

   * `128': selects a 128K Spectrum

   * `plus2': selects a +2

   * `plus2a': selects a +2A

   * `plus3': selects a +3

   The `-p' option turns a specific peripheral on, whilst the `-q'
turns it off again. Available peripherals are:

   * `if1': Interface I

   * `mgt': An MGT disc interface (otherwise known as Disciple/+D)

   * `samram': SamRam

   Note that if the same peripheral is given to both a `-p' and a `-q'
option, it will be turned *off*.


@EndNode

@Node "Verbose" "snapconv.info/Verbose"
@Next "R register"
@Prev "Changing hardware"
@Toc "Invoking SnapConv"

Making SnapConv more verbose
============================

   The `-v' option makes SnapConv more verbose. One `-v' option will
produce some additional diagnostic messages to standard error, whilst
two or more will produce a large number.


@EndNode

@Node "R register" "snapconv.info/R register"
@Prev "Verbose"
@Toc "Invoking SnapConv"

Problems with the R register
============================

   The R register is used by the z80 to control memory refresh.
Generally, R is accessible only via `LD R,A' and `LD A,R', and this pair
of instructions gives identical results on all emulators. However, this
is implemented differently on different emulators: after a `XOR A/LD
R,A' sequence, Gerton Lunter's `z80' sets R to #01, whilst all the
other emulators (which have accurate R register emulation) I have been
able to test set R to #00. This can then cause a problem if the program
is snapped and then transferred from one emulator to another inbetween
a `LD R,A' and a `LD A,R'.

   The `-r' option is designed to solve this problem: it takes one
numeric argument, which is used to correct the R register. The argument
should be -1 when converting from a snap produced by `z80' (note that
this is not the same thing as a `.z80' file) to another emulator, and
+1 when doing the reverse. However, snaps are rarely saved in a place
where the value of R is crucial, so this option is only very rarely
needed at all.


@EndNode

@Node "File Formats" "snapconv.info/File Formats"
@Next "ROMs"
@Prev "Invoking SnapConv"
@Toc "Main"

Supported file formats
**********************

   Included here are details on each of the file formats currently
supported by SnapConv. Each entry lists the extension which SnapConv
uses to recognise this format, the argument to the `-i' and `-o'
options (see @{"Running SnapConv" Link "Invoking SnapConv"}) which is used to specify this format and
then details on the format itself.


 @{" PlusD " Link "PlusD"} 
 @{" scr " Link "scr"} 
 @{" sna " Link "sna"} 
 @{" snp " Link "snp"} 
 @{" sp " Link "sp"} 
 @{" z80 " Link "z80"} 
 @{" zxs " Link "zxs"} 


@EndNode

@Node "PlusD" "snapconv.info/PlusD"
@Next "scr"
@Prev "File Formats"
@Toc "File Formats"

Plus D snapshots
================

Default extension
     None

Format name
     `plusd'

   This is the snapshot format used by Romantic Robot's +D interface, as
well as the Spectrum emulator on the SAM Coup'e. I haven't actually
tested that it works, as I don't have a +D or a SAM to test it on. It
supports 48K snapshots only.

   One problem with this format is that it stores six bytes of data on
the program's stack, which can cause corruption if the snap was taken
at a critical point.


@EndNode

@Node "scr" "snapconv.info/scr"
@Next "sna"
@Prev "PlusD"
@Toc "File Formats"

`.scr' files
============

Default extension
     `.scr'

Format name
     `scr'

   This is not a snap format, but is the common extension used for a
binary image of the Spectrum's video RAM. Note that *you cannot convert
from .scr files*.

   The arrangement of the Spectrum's video RAM is not trivial, so unless
you know what you are doing, the most likely thing you are going to want
to do with a `.scr' file is to convert into into a `normal' graphics
format; there are various utilities available on the Internet to do
this, for example Martijn van der Heide's `scr2gif', available from
`http://www.void.demon.nl/scr2gif.html', or the `CONVERT' program
supplied with the registered version of Gerton Lunter's `z80'.
(`scr2gif' is also distributed in the `xzx' contrib archive).


@EndNode

@Node "sna" "snapconv.info/sna"
@Next "snp"
@Prev "scr"
@Toc "File Formats"

`.sna' snapshots
================

Default extension
     `.sna'

Format name
     `sna' (also `sna48' and `sna128', see below)

   The 48K version of this format originated on the Mirage Microdriver,
but is now supported by almost every emulator. The main problem with
this format is that it stores PC on the program's stack, which can cause
corrupt data if the snap was taken at a critical point.

   128K `.sna' files are not nearly so widely supported, being
supported by only one or two emulators. They do have the advantage that
PC is stored separately, so corruption can no longer occur.

   The only way to tell whether a `.sna' file is a 48K or 128K snap is
by the file size, which is not available if the file is being read from
a device or a pipe; in this case, it is necessary to tell SnapConv
whether the file is a 48K or 128K snap by using the `-i sna48' and `-i
sna128' commands. (These two options work exactly the same as `sna' if
used with the `-o' option).


@EndNode

@Node "snp" "snapconv.info/snp"
@Next "sp"
@Prev "sna"
@Toc "File Formats"

`.snp' snapshots
================

Default extension
     `.snp'

Format name
     `snp'

   The only emulator I know of which uses `.snp' files is Nuclear ZX by
Radovan Garabik. There are no known issues regarding this format.


@EndNode

@Node "sp" "snapconv.info/sp"
@Next "z80"
@Prev "snp"
@Toc "File Formats"

`.sp' snapshots
===============

Default extension
     `.sp'

Format name
     `sp'

   The `.sp' format is used by Pedro Gimeno's `SPECTRUM' emulator (and
its earlier version, `VGASPEC'). The only known issue regarding this
format relates to the interpretation of bit 3 of the status word; it is
interpreted as does `SPECTRUM' v0.99f, rather than 0.99e.

   When writing a `.sp' file, you can use one of the `-1' or `-2'
options to select the old (used by `VGASPEC') or new (used by
`SPECTRUM') formats respectively; the default if `-2'.


@EndNode

@Node "z80" "snapconv.info/z80"
@Next "zxs"
@Prev "sp"
@Toc "File Formats"

`.z80' snapshots
================

Default extension
     `.z80'

Format name
     `z80'

   The `.z80' format was originally created by Gerton Lunter for use
with his `z80' emulator, but has now become the dominant format for
128K snaps, and is very close behind .sna for 48K snaps.

   When writing a `.z80' snap, you can use one of the `-1', `-2' and
`-3' options to select a version 1,2 or 3 `.z80' file; the default is
`-3'.

   One known issue with this format relates to the run-length
compression used to encode the data. Starting with version 3.05 of
`z80', Gerton introduced a facility by which the data could be stored
uncompressed (This was intended for use in the pathological case where
the compression increased the size of the data). SnapConv will use this
facility on both version 2 and version 3 `.z80' files (version 1 files
had a different method for supporting uncompressed data), which may
cause problems with some emulators if they do not recognise this
facility.

   SnapConv can also handle the +3 `.z80' snapshots produced by Erik
Kunze's `xzx', and also recognizes the extension introduced by `xzx'
which notes when the AY-3-8192 sound chip is being emulated in a 48k
Spectrum.

   Finally, SnapConv writes the pages into 48K `.z80' files in a
different order from that of other utilities (to be precise, it writes
the pages in the order 5,4,8 as opposed to the 4,5,8 used by everything
else). This is basically due to the internal data structures used by
SnapConv; it shouldn't cause any problems, but I'll mention in here just
in case.


@EndNode

@Node "zxs" "snapconv.info/zxs"
@Prev "z80"
@Toc "File Formats"

`.zxs' snapshots
================

Default extension
     `.zxs'

Format name
     `zxs'

   `.zxs' snapshots are created by Vaggelis Kapartzianis' `zx32'
emulator (also known as "ZX Spectrum Emulator for Windows 95"). This is
a highly flexible file format, with plenty of room for future
extensions.

   One point is that SnapConv will ignore any tape or disk images
stored in the `.zxs' files; if there are any tape/disk images present,
SnapConv will produce warning messages about unknown chunks of types
`tape' (or `tapx' if you're using zx32 1.03.98.0603), `dsk0' and/or
`dsk1' being ignored.


@EndNode

@Node "ROMs" "snapconv.info/ROMs"
@Next "Technical Information"
@Prev "File Formats"
@Toc "Main"

ROMs in snapshot files
**********************

   Currently, this applies only to `.z80' snapshots (see @{"z80" Link "z80"}), as this
is the only snapshot format supported by SnapConv which allows the ROM
currently in use to be stored in the snap.

   Furthermore, most emulators will not write only the RAM to the snap,
and not the ROM(s) in use; the only emulator I know of which writes the
ROMs out is Pedro Salas' `Sinclair'.

   If SnapConv finds a snap with the ROMs in it, it will compare those
ROMs to the standard Spectrum ones, and write them out only if they are
different from the standard ones; which (if any) emulators pay any
attention to the ROMs in the snap is a different question.

   One point here is that there are multiple versions of some of the
ROMs, (I know of 3 versions of the Interface 1 ROM and 2 of the +2A/+3
ROMs) and SnapConv will detect only one of these; if the other versions
are present in the snap, they will be retained.


@EndNode

