@EndNode

@Node "Compiling SnapConv" "snapconv.info/Compiling SnapConv"
@Next "Extending SnapConv"
@Prev "Reference"
@Toc "Technical Information"

Compiling SnapConv
==================

   Compiling SnapConv on a Unix system should be pretty easy; just run
the `configure' shell script, and then `make'. SnapConv can then be
installed via `make install'; you'll almost certainly have to be root
to do this.

   If you have Jean-loup Gaily and Mark Adler's `zlib' library
installed (and working!) on your system, SnapConv will use it to
implement support for deflated `.zxs' snaps. `zlib' is available from
the zlib Home Page, `http://www.cdrom.com/pub/infozip/zlib/'.

   If you're trying to compile SnapConv on an MS-DOS system, simply copy
`Makefile.dos' to `Makefile' and then type `make' (assuming you've got
make installed, of course!). The Makefile is very simplistic, and set
up for use with DJGPP (a DOS port of gcc). You'll probably have to
change the path to `zlib' to suit your setup. If any of this doesn't
work, all you need to do is compile all of the `.c' files in SnapConv's
directory and link them together. Define `HAVE_LIBZ' if you've got
`zlib' and `HAVE_STRCASECMP' if your libraries include the `strcasecmp'
function.


@EndNode

@Node "Extending SnapConv" "snapconv.info/Extending SnapConv"
@Next "File sizes"
@Prev "Compiling SnapConv"
@Toc "Technical Information"

Extending SnapConv
==================

   I've tried to make it fairly easy to add extra snap formats to
SnapConv; internally, all snap formats are converted into two parts:
firstly, a structure of type `snapinfo', which is defined in
`snapinfo.h', and contains information on the current values of the
registers and the like, and well as emulator-specific settings. The
memory contents are stored in `char **pages', an array of 8 character
pointers corresponding to the 128K's pages 0-7. 48K snaps should have
0x4000-0x7fff stored in page 5, 0x8000-0xbfff stored in page 2 and
0xc000-0xffff stored in page 0 (this corresponds to the default mapping
used by the 128K machines). SamRam shadow ram should be stored in pages
3 (0x8000-0xbfff) and 4 (0xc000-0xfff).

   If there are ROMs present in the snap, they should first be compared
against the standard types (see @{"ROMs" Link "ROMs"}) but comparing their Adler-32
checksums to those in `romInfo[].checksum', and then *if non-standard*,
should be stored in `romPages[].ptr'. The flag `romPages[].present'
should be set when the ROM is found, so duplicate copies of one ROM can
be detected.

   The procedure for adding a new snap format is something like:

  1. Write the lower-level functions for reading the header and dealing
     with memory contents, and place these into a source file of their
     own. Two functions which may be useful:

    `construct48KPages'
          This takes a pointer to a 48Kb area of memory, and splits it
          into the correct entries in `char **pages'. (Defined in
          `snapconv.c').

    `construct48KBuffer'
          The reverse of `construct48KPages', this takes `char **pages'
          and fills a 48Kb buffer (which should have been allocated
          previously) with the contents corresponding to the 48K
          machine's memory. (Defined in `snapconv.c').

  2. Write a high-level read function of the form `int NAME(FILE *f,
     char *inName, struct snapinfo *sptr, unsigned char **pages,
     unsigned char **romPages)', where `f' is a pointer to the file to
     be read, `inName' is the name of the file (used for error
     messages), `sptr' is the information on the snap, `pages' is the
     snap's RAM contents, and `romPages' is the contents of any
     non-standard ROMs. By the time this function gets control, all
     entries in `sptr' will have been set to sensible defaults, and
     every entry in `pages' and `romPages[].ptr' will be 0.

  3. Write a high-level write function of the form `int NAME(FILE *f,
     char *outName, int version, struct snapinfo *sptr, unsigned char
     **pages, unsigned char **romPages)'. The arguments here are
     basically the same as those for the read function, except for
     `version', which specifies which version of the format should be
     written. If any of the read or write functions discovers an error,
     they should return one of the `ERROR_xxx' codes defined in
     `snapconv.h' (Extend this if you need to by adding to the enum,
     adding a corresponding message in `errorMessages' in `snapconv.c',
     and incrementing `numErrorMessages'). If no error is discovered,
     return `ERROR_NONE'.

  4. Add an entry to `supportedTypes' in `snapconv.c' giving the new
     snap format's extension (if any), an ID to use with the `-i' and
     `-o' options, and your read and write functions. Increment
     `numSupportedTypes'.

  5. Finally, various bits of housekeeping: remember to `#include' the
     header file for your low level functions, and add your new files to
     `Makefile'.

   With the systems mentioned above in place, adding a simple snapshot
format is very quick: the +D format took me only 30 minutes to get up
and running.


 @{" Hardware maps " Link "Hardware maps"}                Dealing with unsupported hardware


@EndNode

@Node "Hardware maps" "snapconv.info/Hardware maps"
@Prev "Extending SnapConv"
@Toc "Extending SnapConv"

Dealing with unsupported hardware
---------------------------------

   SnapConv includes a flexible system for dealing with snapshot formats
which do not support all the machine types and/or peripherals which
SnapConv knows about. The work is done by at `unsupportedHardware'
function (defined in `hardware.c', which takes three parameters:

  1. A pointer to the snap information structure

  2. An array of the hardware maps to be applied (see below)

  3. A format string to be used in any messages printed

   Each hardware map for the second argument must be of type hardwareMap
(defined in `hardware.h'), which has six fields:

  1. The machine type for which this map applies (see the `MACHINE_xxx'
     enum defined in `snapconv.h').

  2. The peripherals which must be active for this map to apply (see
     `PERIPH_xxx' in `snapconv.h'). Note that multiple peripherals must
     (counter-intuitvely) combined using OR, not AND.

  3. The machine type to change to.

  4. The peripherals to switch on.

  5. The peripherals to switch off.

  6. A message to be printed, telling the user what has happened. This
     should contain precisely one `%s', which will be replaced by the
     format string passed to `unsupportedHardware'.

   The list of hardware maps must terminate with a map which has
`UNSUPPORTED_LAST' as its first field.

   If the first field of the map is `UNSUPPORTED_SPECIAL', a special
map, selected by the third field, is applied. Available special maps
are:

   * `UNSUPPORTED_SPECIAL128K': select the standard 48K machine.

   * `UNSUPPORTED_SPECIALNEW': select either the 48K or base 128K
     machine.

   * `UNSUPPORTED_SPECIALPERIPH': turn off all peripherals

   The special code `UNSUPPORTED_ANY' can also be used in the first
field to make a map which applies for any machine, and
`UNSUPPORTED_NOCHANGE' can be used in the third field to create a map
which affects peripherals only.

   There are also four pre-defined maps:

   * `UNSUPPORTED_END': this is simply a map with `UNSUPPORTED_LAST' as
     its first field.

   * `UNSUPPORTED_128KMACHINES': a map using the
     `UNSUPPORTED_SPECIAL128K' special, with an appropriate message.

   * `UNSUPPORTED_NEWMACHINES': the `UNSUPPORTED_SPECIALNEW' special.

   * `UNSUPPORTED_PERIPHS': the `UNSUPPORTED_SPECIALPERIPH' special.

   These four maps correspond to special values allowed, but you may
wish to use your own if you wish for a different message from the
default.

   Finally, there are also two complete arrays of maps defined:

   * `UNSUPPORTED_48KNOPERIPHS': this selects a 48K machine with no
     special peripherals.

   * `UNSUPPORTED_128KNOPERIPHS': this selects the 48K/base 128K with no
     peripherals.


@EndNode

@Node "File sizes" "snapconv.info/File sizes"
@Prev "Extending SnapConv"
@Toc "Technical Information"

File sizes from `zx32' and SnapConv
===================================

   Q: Why are the `.zxs' files produced by `zx32' and SnapConv of the
same program different sizes?

   A: There are (at least) three reasons:

  1. You haven't got `zx32' set to use maximum compression; SnapConv
     always uses the equivalent of maximum compression.

  2. When `zx32' produces a `.zxs' file, it adds an empty chunk of type
     `LIST' to the file, and SnapConv doesn't.

  3. SnapConv uses `zlib' to provide for its deflation/inflation
     support, whilst `zx32' uses Info-ZIP. Whilst the routines in
     `zlib' and Info-ZIP are written by the same people (Jean-loup
     Gailly and Mark Adler), they do appear to produce slightly
     different output in certain cases.


@EndNode

